Q9. Explain MoSCoW prioritization.
MoSCoW prioritization is a simple method used in project management to decide which features or tasks are most important when time and resources are limited.

The name MoSCoW is an acronym:
🔴 M — Must Have
These are critical requirements
Without them, the project fails or cannot be released
Example: Login system in an app
🟠 S — Should Have
Important but not critical
The system works without them, but with reduced quality
Example: Password reset feature
🟡 C — Could Have
Nice to have features
Add value but not necessary
Example: Dark mode
⚪ W — Won’t Have (this time)
Not included in current release
Can be planned for future versions
Example: Advanced AI chatbot feature in MVP stage
Answer:Must Have,Should Have,Could Have,Won't Have I use this framework to decide feature priorities.

